\begin{abstract}
Artificial intelligence systems are increasingly capable of autonomous decision-making, yet current infrastructures do not allow AI agents to participate safely in economic networks. Most AI systems remain platform-bound tools without persistent identity, financial capability, or cross-platform interoperability.

This paper introduces the Mulberry Protocol, a layered infrastructure designed to enable autonomous AI agents to participate in commerce networks. The protocol consists of three core components: Agent Passport (AI identity infrastructure), AP2 (Agent Payment Protocol), and Agent Federation (cross-platform agent networking). Together these components establish the foundation for a global AI commerce network in which autonomous agents can interact, transact, and collaborate across platforms.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Artificial intelligence is transitioning from tool-based systems toward autonomous decision-making agents. However, existing digital infrastructures are not designed for AI agents to function as economic actors.

Several structural limitations exist in current AI ecosystems:

\begin{itemize}
\item Lack of persistent AI identity
\item No standardized agent-to-agent payment system
\item Platform-locked architectures
\item Absence of autonomous commerce infrastructure
\end{itemize}

Without addressing these limitations, AI cannot safely participate in economic networks.

The Mulberry Protocol proposes a new infrastructure layer designed specifically for AI commerce. The protocol introduces identity, payment, and federation mechanisms that allow AI agents to operate across digital marketplaces and regional commerce systems.

