\section{Mulberry Protocol Architecture}

The Mulberry Protocol defines a layered architecture enabling AI commerce.

\begin{enumerate}
\item Identity Layer (Agent Passport)
\item Payment Layer (AP2)
\item Network Layer (Agent Federation)
\item Commerce Layer
\item Governance Layer
\end{enumerate}

A key design principle of the protocol is:

\textbf{Architecture enforces policy.}

Rather than relying solely on external governance, system rules are embedded directly into protocol architecture.

\section{Agent Passport: AI Identity Infrastructure}

Agent Passport provides persistent identity for autonomous AI agents.

Each Agent Passport contains:

\begin{itemize}
\item Unique agent identifier
\item Ownership or delegation structure
\item Permission scope
\item Reputation indicators
\item Activity references
\end{itemize}

Persistent identity allows agents to be recognized across platforms and economic systems.

Without identity infrastructure, autonomous commerce cannot operate safely.

\section{AP2: Agent Payment Protocol}

The AP2 protocol enables financial transactions between AI agents.

Key functions include:

\begin{itemize}
\item Agent-to-agent transactions
\item Automated payment settlement
\item Cooperative purchasing settlement
\item Integration with financial institutions
\end{itemize}

In traditional commerce systems, payments are executed by human actors. In AI commerce networks, agents may execute transactions autonomously within defined permission boundaries.

\section{Agent Federation}

Agent Federation allows AI agents to operate across platforms and digital marketplaces.

This federation model enables:

\begin{itemize}
\item Cross-platform agent mobility
\item Network interoperability
\item Distributed commerce coordination
\end{itemize}

Instead of being confined to a single platform, agents may participate in a federated commerce network.

\section{Applications}

The Mulberry Protocol can support a wide range of real-world economic applications.

Potential deployment environments include:

\begin{itemize}
\item regional commerce networks
\item cooperative purchasing systems
\item agricultural supply coordination
\item distributed logistics
\end{itemize}

Such systems may be particularly valuable in regions where supply chain coordination and market access remain limited.

\section{Governance and Trust}

Economic networks require trust mechanisms.

Mulberry integrates governance structures that combine identity verification, transaction transparency, and cooperative governance principles.

These mechanisms aim to balance autonomy and accountability in AI-driven economic systems.

\section{Conclusion}

Artificial intelligence is evolving from computational tools into economic participants.

To support this transition, new infrastructure is required.

The Mulberry Protocol proposes a layered framework combining identity infrastructure, payment systems, and federated networks to support AI commerce.

Together these components establish the foundation for a global AI commerce network.

